{
    "__README__": "Canonical OTN alarm catalog -- single source of truth. Consumed by (1) the SAI HAL-event listener (event_id -> alarm), (2) otn-vhal (user CLI), and mirrored into the device eventd profile (default.json). Encoding follows Shasta's OOP dev-event model: event_id selects the alarm AND raise-vs-clear (distinct raise_id / clear_id), and the payload's sub_event_id carries the instance. Alarm attributes follow the OpenROADM model (org-openroadm-alarm / -resource-types) via alarm_type + resource_type.",
    "__notes__": "Two sources on one socket, one encoding: (A) real Shasta HAL dev-events -- category 'hal-event', using the actual DEF_EVENT_ID_* raise/clear pairs from util-lib/util_event.h (OA/WSS/OSC/OTDR/OCM comm-fails; a genuine Shasta HAL frame decodes here). Only the clearable comm-fail pairs are included -- Shasta's notify-only triggers (FAN/PWR/CPU) are excluded because they have no clear id and aren't standalone alarms. (B) OLS/derived OpenROADM alarms (thermal/fan/power/optical incl. amp LOS/ORL/APR) that never travel as HAL dev-events -- assigned reserved ids >= 4096 so otn-vhal can inject them on the KVM. eventd severities are UPPERCASE (CRITICAL|MAJOR|MINOR|WARNING|INFORMATIONAL); alarm_type/resource_type are the OpenROADM classification. Severity/type/resource are proposed classifications for review.",
